D_1(\mathbb{R},\mathbb{C}) \rightarrow D_0(\mathbb{R}, \mathbb{C})
f \in \mathrm{dom}\,\nabla
x \in \mathbb{R}
\nabla(f)(x) = \lim^{\mathbb{R}}_{h \rightarrow 0}\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}
f \in D_1(\mathbb{R},\mathbb{C}), c \in \mathbb{C}.
x \in \mathbb{R},
\nabla(cf)(x) = \lim^{\mathbb{R}}_{h \rightarrow 0}\frac{cf(x+h)-cf(x)}{h} = c\left(\lim^\mathbb{R}_{h \rightarrow 0}\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}\right)=c\nabla(f)(x)
\nabla(cf)  = c \nabla(f),
x
f(x)=c g(x)
h(x)=c
f(x)=h(x)g(x)
f'(x)=h'(x)g(x)+g'(x)h(x)
f'(x)=0\cdot g(x)+g'(x)h(x)=h(x)g'(x)=cg'(x)
\lim_{x\rightarrow y}{\frac{h(y)-h(x)}{y-x}}=\lim_{x\rightarrow y}{\frac{c-c}{x-y}}=\lim_{x\rightarrow y}{0}=0
\lim_{x\rightarrow y}{cf(x)}=c\lim_{x\rightarrow y}{f(x)}
(cf)'(x)=\lim_{x\rightarrow y}{\frac{cf(y)-cf(x)}{y-x}}=c\lim_{x\rightarrow y}{\frac{f(y)-f(x)}{x-y}}= cf'(x).
